author = {William A. Mackaness},
keywords = {Cartesian space, Digital cartographic model, Digital landscape model, NHD, NMA, USGS},
abstract = {Maps are an intuitive means of understanding the geographic complexity of the world—from observations at the finest level of detail to that of the global scale. The human cartographer is central to the task of designing and producing multiscale maps but this task has now achieved very high levels of automation by utilizing a broad range of computer-based methodologies. Map generalization in the context of automated mapping is a set of techniques for automatically deriving topographic and thematic maps at smaller scales, from detailed, large-scale maps. Developments in model generalization are in response to the need to select and manage large volumes of data while cartographic generalization is a set of techniques concerned with the optimal arrangement and symbolization of geographic data. There now exists a diverse range of map generalization algorithms. Importantly there is an increasing realization of the importance of automated evaluation techniques in order to develop fully automated solutions—i.e., systems that require no human intervention. Map generalization techniques are also highly relevant to social media mapping, particularly in the context of mobile technologies. Given the ever widening diversity of data sources, it is important to reflect on the importance of map generalization techniques in data fusion and the importance of modeling quality control among heterogenous global datasets that vary in space and time.}
